<DOC><DOCNO> AP881011-0109 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-11-88 1301EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-CountryMusic     10-11 0525</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Country Music,0542</SECOND><HEAD>Hank Williams Jr. Still Reigns As King of Country</HEAD><BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hank Williams Jr., still reigning asNashville's top entertainer, celebrated twin honors from theCountry Music Association with word that he'll release as a duet anewfound recording made by his legendary father.   Through modern technology, Williams, 39, will be able to joinhis late dad on the recording, to be released in February. Thesong, ``There's a Tear in My Beer,'' was cut by Williams Sr. in1952, less than a year before he died.   ``It's an absolute treasure,'' Williams said Monday night. ``Iget chills playing it.''   Vocals by the younger Williams will be added to the originaltrack.   Hank Williams Sr. was a country music pioneer with hits like``Your Cheatin' Heart'' and ``I'm So Lonesome I Could Cry.''   ``I hope in my best day I can sing as good as he did,'' Williamssaid as the Country Music Association gave him its vote ofconfidence at the 22nd awards Monday night.   Williams was named entertainer of the year for the second timein a row and also won the trophy for best album, ``Born to Boogie.''   The only other double winner was K.T. Oslin, who was votedfemale vocalist of the year and won best song for her poignant``80's Ladies.''   Williams explained that he tries to reach the common man withhis turbocharged blend of country, rock 'n' roll and blues.   ``I try to sing my songs for everyday folks and it all workedout,'' he said. ``I try to tear 'em up before I get off the stage.''   Oslin has been singing country music professionally for just twoyears after minor roles on Broadway and making televisioncommercials for items such as denture products.   ``I have electric light switches where I used to have chains,''she said about the change in her life since 1986.   She said the two awards will mean ``more bucks, honey, morebucks.''   Randy Travis, whose album ``Always andamp; Forever'' has sold 3million copies, was voted male vocalist of the year for the secondstraight time.   His award met with the approval of Roy Acuff, the 85-year-old``king of country music,'' who was wearing a jacket backstage thatsaid ``Randy Travis, Back to Country'' on it.   The Judds, a mother-daughter duet, were voted No. 1 duo afterwinning group of the year three straight years. They were placed inthe duo category this year under a rules change.   Kathy Mattea's ``18 Wheels and a Dozen Roses'' was voted No. 1single record. The four-piece vocal band Highway 101 won theirfirst CMA award, group of the year.   Ricky Van Shelton won the Horizon Award for a promising newcomerand veteran guitarist Chet Atkins was voted No. 1 instrumentalistfor the ninth time. The vocal event, a new award given to two ormore singers who do not normally perform together, went to DollyParton, Linda Ronstadt and Emmylou Harris for their ``Trio'' album.   Country queen Loretta Lynn and cowboy singer Roy Rogers werevoted into the Country Music Hall of Fame.</TEXT></DOC>